#import crude oil dataset for years 2004-2016 into a dataframe
crudeOil = read.table('crudeoil_w0416.csv', header=T, sep=',')
# create time series for crudeOil prices
crudeOil_ts = zoo(crudeOil$price, as.Date(as.character(crudeOil$date), format = "%d-%b-%y"))
#To retrieve only dates use
head(time(crudeOil_ts))
## [1] "2004-01-02" "2004-01-09" "2004-01-16" "2004-01-23" "2004-01-30"
## [6] "2004-02-06"
# Retrieve start date
start(crudeOil_ts)
## [1] "2004-01-02"
# Retrieve End date
end(crudeOil_ts)
## [1] "2016-01-01"
# sort data in chronological order
# set variable date as time/date variable
crudeOil$date=as.Date(as.character(crudeOil$date), format = "%m/%d/%y")
crudeOil=crudeOil[order(crudeOil$date),]

# create lagged series using function lag(tsobject, k==1);
pricelag = lag(crudeOil_ts, k=-1);
head(pricelag)
## 2004-01-09 2004-01-16 2004-01-23 2004-01-30 2004-02-06 2004-02-13 
##      32.68      33.89      34.51      35.45      33.61      33.41
# diff = p_t - p_(t-1);
pricedif = diff(crudeOil_ts);
#compute simple returns ret = (p_t-p_(t-1))/p_(t-1)
ret=(crudeOil_ts-pricelag)/pricelag

#Example of data analysis for crudeOil dataset
#DEFINE LOG RETURNS
#rts is a time series object since it is created from a TS object
rts = diff(log(crudeOil_ts))
#to retrieve numerical values from time series use coredata()
# rt is a numerical vector (no date information)
rt=coredata(rts)
#print first 6 values
head(rt)

## [6]  0.013969613

### Exercise 3 Lubridate package R-bloggers: https://www.r-bloggers.com/dates-and-times-simple-and-easy-with-lubridate-exercises-part-1/

#install.packages("lubridate")
library(lubridate)
## 
## Attaching package: 'lubridate'
## The following object is masked from 'package:base':
## 
##     date
#1.Populate a variable called start_date with a date representation of string 23012017
start_date = dmy("23012017")

#2.Use the lubridate function today to print the current date
today()
## [1] "2018-10-28"
#3.Extract the year part from the start_date variable
year(start_date)
## [1] 2017
#4.Extract the month part from the start_date variable
month(start_date)
## [1] 1
#5.Extract the day part from the start_date variable
day(start_date)
## [1] 23
#6.Set the month in variable start_date to February
month(start_date) <- 2

#7.Add 6 days to variable start_date.
#the month value auto-increased to march to adjust for the date increase
start_date + days(6)
## [1] "2017-03-01"
#8.Substract 3 months from variable start_date
start_date - months(3)
## [1] "2016-11-23"
#9.Populate a field called concatenated_dates with a vector of dates containing the following values: 31.12.2015, 01.01.2016, 15.02.2016
concatenated_dates <- dmy(c("31.12.2015", "01.01.2016",  "15.02.2016"))
concatenated_dates
## [1] "2015-12-31" "2016-01-01" "2016-02-15"
#10.Calculate in a short and simple way the addition of 1 thru 10 days to start_date variable
start_date + c(1:10) * days(1)
##  [1] "2017-02-24" "2017-02-25" "2017-02-26" "2017-02-27" "2017-02-28"
##  [6] "2017-03-01" "2017-03-02" "2017-03-03" "2017-03-04" "2017-03-05"
